metadata.name: GEN XYZ Das Occult #4174
metadata.description:
A 10k Generative Profile Pic collection
GEN XYZ Das Occult - by culla - @tamccullough

move over cryptopunks
there is a new group on the scene

100% code - not an image composition

A bunch of common palettes
A selection of rare palettes
And a smaller set of ultra rare palettes
However, rarity will be based on what combinations the code produces

The majority of tokens will not have a special trait
However your token might have one or even multiple special traits
But, be aware that only the last special trait added will be listed in the features

Even then, look closely, because not all aspects of the canvas are included in the features. Collectors should still look closely and choose what they like when buying on secondary.

Which team are you on? X or O?

follow culla on twitter for updates. Or maybe __acolyte__

If the non reserved tokens mint out quickly, Access List mints will have 24 hours to mint reserves assigned to those wallets

Thank you for supporting an emerging artist in the generative art space

Access List reserves were given to holders of the following PFP collections created by culla
2x for each Basqunk held
1x for each Inkspunk, TwoFourQunk, V0iD, DeeManz, Punkasso and CR0$$KULL
You would have needed to transfer the above tokens to your mint wallet at the time of the snapshot

share your tokens on social media with #genxyznft
Made with love by culla using p5.js

metadata.name: Acequia #237
metadata.description:
Acequia (“ah-seh-kee-uh”) - a Spanish adaptation of the Arabic word as-sāqiya, meaning “water carrier”. 

In our second collaboration, Rich and Rick are back with our blend of generative code, intricate design, attention to detail, and a splash of charm. 

 Acequias are traditional irrigation canals used to distribute rainwater and snowmelt along a complex network of narrow channels. They are found in Spain, the American Southwest, and northern Mexico, where they are essential for sustaining fields, orchards, and gardens in semi-arid regions.   
Our aim in this series is to capture the essence of these waterways in bold geometric designs. Each piece is inspired by a mountain village or town in Andalusia (southern Spain). 

The location determines the cube designs and construction rules that are used to build the final output. These are combined with striking day/night palettes, outline styles, scales, climates, and a few surprises of course!


Controls (in live view): 

- Press [p] to pause water animation 
- Press [e] to complete water animation 
- Press [r] to reset water animation 
- Press [s] to save the current image 
- Press [h] for a high-res output suitable for printing 
- Press [b] to toggle the border

metadata.name: Coronado #370
metadata.description:
This series is about the beauty and charm of imperfection, chaos amidst order, and letting go. It's about knowing that however much control we think we may have, things can all fall apart or burst into something unexpectedly wonderful at any moment, even without our hands tightly on the reigns.

Please see fxtext article linked from main project page for more background on the project and rendering notes.

Some key commands in live mode:

G : Toggle grain
S : Save current resolution
1 : 4000x5000
2 : 6000x7500
3 : 8000x10000
4 : 10000x12500
5 : 12000x15000
6 : 14000x17500
(1-6 work best on Chrome)
(rendering takes longer as resolution increases)

objkt.name: E R E B U S #17

metadata.name: E R E B U S #17
metadata.description:
Fragments of minds

Our daily life is filled with automatisms, habits that make our comfort zone. Then one day an event occurs that touches us deeply. We step out of our comfort zone, an internal emotional tornado is unleashed in our consciousness. This work tries to illustrate this flow of passion, this emotional violence on the fabric of daily life.

About features.
There are 3 random characteristics:

1. Latent state of mind
This feature correspond to the lines in the background. ‘Healthy’ is the most frequent, and the other types appear more rarely (’Psychotic’ is really rare).

2. Crystallization

This feature corresponds to the strength of the flow of the passion in our mind. Probability : ‘Normal’ = 77%, ‘Strong’ = 33%.

3. Disturbance
The disturbance rate is ’Low’ (frequent), or ‘High’ (rare).

When a work is collected, a process of synchronicity is triggered. Synchronicity is a process of randomness that allows us to communicate with our unconscious (psychological paradigm) or with the hidden forces of the universe (spiritual paradigm). The rarer an image is, the more it represents an exceptional psychic state.

To print a high resolution image (resolution is 6400*6400px.), press [p].
To print a screen resolution image, right-clic then ‘save image’.

This artwork celebrate the anniversary of FxHash - Happy Birthday little baby :-)
50% of primary sales are donate to the Processing Foundation (thank you for making my days better).

Artwork by @GenerativePunk.

metadata.name: Bardez #220
metadata.description:
Bardez is the Armenian word for garden. It is etymologically tied to an ancient word for paradise, but that link goes deeper than etymology. Gardens have always been small pieces of paradise for me, and hearing the word in Armenian triggers a flood of warm memories.

Memories of wandering around my grandfather’s garden, plucking ripe plums and figs from their branches.
Memories of playing in my parents yard, the scent of jasmine in the summer heat.
Of sun warmed tomatoes in my mom’s vegetable patch.
The smell of dirt and grass.
Mud on my hands.
Sun on my skin.
Memories of paradise.

I hope you enjoy these gardens I’ve planted, and I hope they remind you of some warm and wonderful memories.
 
Nat Sarkissian






Notes:
 - This piece uses a shader to compute the lighting of the terrain in the first frame. If you don’t have a graphics card, you may have difficulty running this.

 - Append “&mag=N” to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done. The maximum resolution seems to be limited by what your web browser allows. I have been able to output up to 11140px tall and wide using Firefox, which should be enough detail for prints up to 37x37 inches. I recommend keeping the console open while attempting larger renders. It will show you the progress of the render, and also show you if you have attempted too large a render for your system. N can be any positive whole or decimal number greater than or equal to 1.

 - Finally, collectors at the highest tier will be entitled to a signed print of their edition. For further details and updates, keep an eye on my Twitter (@_NatSarkissian).

metadata.name: Perlin's Jungle #79
metadata.description:
This is a jungle of Perlin noise with 13 different patterns. This work is fully responsive.

(Because of the algorithm, the width of the strokes and details could be different with the same hash. But overall they look the same.)

The animation will pause at frame 3200. 
- Press = "P" to pause/unpause the animation.
- Press = "s" to save high resolution image.

metadata.name: Obliques #143
metadata.description:
Obliques are a reinterpretation of Parallels, a collection of AI generated color fields by Marc Maurer. Many of the pieces in that collection are CC0, which basically means they can be reused for other projects, like this one.

Obliques takes artifacts from Parallels and uses them as brushes, painting slices of the original image on the canvas in a (hopefully) pleasant, chaotic way.

About 10% will be "Glitched".

The "Source Material" property will tell you the name of piece that it is using.

You can see Marc Maurer's Parallels project here:
https://objkt.com/collection/KT1TiSEcASGD19SW8bmqrqgSgCBkwXqDdTJ1

Obliques are also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

G : Toggle Grain
M : Toggle Matte
S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

metadata.name: Colored Elementary Cellular Automaton #319
metadata.description:
The algorithm is based on Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton. 
This is a 1D cellular automaton with a neighborhood of 5 cells. This gives us 2^5 = 32 patterns for a neighborhood and 2^32 = 4.29B possible combinations!!! The size of the cell varies in a range of 2 to 8. There is a 15% of getting a black and white art.

Pattern rarity:
- Pattern 1 _25%
- Pattern 2 _30%
- Pattern 3 _35%
- Pattern 4 _15%

Note: The art might look in different resolutions because of the responsive view, but the color, pattern, and layout remain the same.
